Character vs factor data

character data: plotted alphabetically

factor data: plotted in order of factor levels

df <- tibble(chardata = c("cold", "warm", "hot", "hot", "warm", "warm", "cold", "cold", "cold"), 
    factordata = factor(c("cold", "warm", "hot", "hot", "warm", "warm", "cold", "cold", "cold"), 
                                 levels = c("cold", "warm", "hot")))

Summary of useful forcats functions

fct_recode(x, ...) â€“ change names of levels

fct_inorder(x) â€“ set level order of x to row order

fct_relevel(x, ...) â€“ manually set the order of levels of x

fct_reorder(x, y) â€“ reorder x by y

fct_infreq(x) â€“ order the levels of x by decreasing frequency

fct_rev(x) â€“ reverse the order of factor levels of x

fct_explicit_na(x) â€“ turn NAs into a real factor level

fct_lump_n(x) â€“ lumps all levels except for the n most frequent

fct_lump_min(x) â€“ lumps levels that appear fewer than min times

Recoding factor levels: fct_recode()

df <- data.frame(name = factor(c("STAT-UN-1201", "STAT-GR-5702",
                                 "STAT-GR-5293")),
                 enrollment = c(86, 172, 12))
df2 <- df
levels(df2$name) = c("Intro", "EDAV", "IMLV")
df2
##    name enrollment
## 1  IMLV         86
## 2  EDAV        172
## 3 Intro         12
# better approach

df$name <- fct_recode(df$name, Intro = "STAT-UN-1201", EDAV = "STAT-GR-5702",
                      IMLV = "STAT-GR-5293")
df
##    name enrollment
## 1 Intro         86
## 2  EDAV        172
## 3  IMLV         12

Set factor level order to row order

x <- factor(c("Jack", "Queen", "King", "Ace"))
levels(x)
## [1] "Ace"   "Jack"  "King"  "Queen"
fct_inorder(x)
## [1] Jack  Queen King  Ace  
## Levels: Jack Queen King Ace

Using fct_relevel() to move levels to the beginning

x <- c("A", "B", "C", "move1", "D", "E", "move2", "F")

fct_relevel(x, "move1", "move2")
## [1] A     B     C     move1 D     E     move2 F    
## Levels: move1 move2 A B C D E F

Using fct_relevel() to move levels after an item (by position)

x <- c("A", "B", "C", "move1", "D", "E", "move2", "F")

fct_relevel(x, "move1", "move2", after = 4) # move after the fourth item
## [1] A     B     C     move1 D     E     move2 F    
## Levels: A B C D move1 move2 E F

Using fct_relevel() to move levels to the end

x <- c("A", "B", "C", "move1", "D", "E", "move2", "F")

fct_relevel(x, "move1", "move2", after = Inf)
## [1] A     B     C     move1 D     E     move2 F    
## Levels: A B C D E F move1 move2

Set factor level to the order of another variable

levels(iris$Species)
## [1] "setosa"     "versicolor" "virginica"
ggplot(iris, aes(x = fct_reorder(Species, Sepal.Width, median), y = Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  coord_flip()

Order factor levels by reverse frequency count

x <- factor(c("Jack", "Queen", "King", "Ace", "Queen", "King", "King"))
levels(x)
## [1] "Ace"   "Jack"  "King"  "Queen"
fct_infreq(x)
## [1] Jack  Queen King  Ace   Queen King  King 
## Levels: King Queen Ace Jack

Dealing with NAs

df <- data.frame(temperature = factor(c("cold", "warm", "hot", NA)),
                 count = c(15, 5, 22, 12))

df %>% 
  mutate(temperature = fct_explicit_na(temperature, "NA") %>% 
           fct_relevel("NA", "hot", "warm", "cold")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = temperature, y = count)) +
  geom_col(color = mycolor, fill = myfill) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_grey(16)

Percentages, more than one group

shortcut method (be careful!)

df %>% 
  group_by(Class, Survived) %>%    # grouped by Class, Survived
  summarize(Freq = sum(Freq)) %>%   # grouped by Class only
  mutate(prop = Freq/sum(Freq)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## # A tibble: 8 Ã— 4
##   Class Survived  Freq  prop
##   <fct> <fct>    <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 1st   No         122 0.375
## 2 1st   Yes        203 0.625
## 3 2nd   No         167 0.586
## 4 2nd   Yes        118 0.414
## 5 3rd   No         528 0.748
## 6 3rd   Yes        178 0.252
## 7 Crew  No         673 0.760
## 8 Crew  Yes        212 0.240

Percentages, more than one group

shortcut method (be careful!)

df %>%    
  group_by(Survived, Class) %>%    # grouped by Survived, Class ORDER MATTERS
  summarize(Freq = sum(Freq)) %>%   # grouped by Survived only
  mutate(prop = Freq/sum(Freq)) %>% 
  ungroup()
